problems.statement:
(i) Given that $a, b, c$ are sides of a triangle, explain why $c < a + b$, $a < b + c$, $b < a + c$.

(ii) Conversely, with a diagram, show that any positive $a, b, c$ satisfying these strict inequalities form a triangle.

(iii) For triangle sides $a, b, c$, decide for each set whether they always / sometimes / never form a triangle:
  (A) $a + 1, b + 1, c + 1$;
  (B) $a/b, b/c, c/a$;
  (C) $|a - b|, |b - c|, |c - a|$;
  (D) $a^2 + bc, b^2 + ca, c^2 + ab$.

(iv) Suppose $f$ is defined on positive reals with $f(x) > f(y) > 0$ but $\dfrac{f(x)}{x} < \dfrac{f(y)}{y}$ whenever $x > y > 0$. Show that $f(a), f(b), f(c)$ are also triangle sides whenever $a, b, c$ are.
